This feature was available, it is not anymore : why? is there a plugin for this?

I would like the Confluence search to work like leading-edge search engines, such as Google, which are already doing this. This will contribute to a much better user experience with the search, it will improve "findability".

Here is a good example. A commonly-misspelled word in my wiki is "Xcelsius". Instead of displaying no search results if someone types, for example, "Excelsius" instead at the top of the search results page, say "Did You Mean Xcelsius?" and display those search results.

In the latest versions of the Oracle setup docs for Confluence there are 2 steps to make the Oracle database user:
* https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/database-setup-for-oracle-173821.html
* https://confluence.atlassian.com/conf65/database-setup-for-oracle-939701687.html

One prompts the customer to "2. Create database user", and the other to "2. Create user with schema-creation privileges". But they are essentially running the same thing:
{code:sql}
create user <user> identified by <password> default tablespace <tablespace_name> quota unlimited on <tablespace_name>;
grant connect to <user>;
grant resource to <user>;
grant create table to <user>;
grant create sequence to <user>;
grant create trigger to <user>;
{code}

VS:
{code:sql}
create user <user> identified by <password> default tablespace <tablespace_name> quota unlimited on <tablespace_name>;
grant connect to <user>;
grant resource to <user>;
grant create table to <user>;
grant create sequence to <user>;
grant create trigger to <user>;
{code}

I've set up Confluence previously with Oracle and can confirm that only one user is needed. I've tried setting up Confluence 6.6 with Oracle 12c but I'm running into an encoding issue (due to the latest database checks) so I can't confirm currently. Did something change in the required set up for Oracle?

Older versions of this guide are more clear, and only include one step to create a user:
https://confluence.atlassian.com/conf64/database-setup-for-oracle-936511497.html

I didn't want to just make the changes and I'm wondering if they were done on purpose.

h4. Issue Description
Confluence Questions add-on has an API available for users who wish to query information from the add-on through REST calls. Among its several resources, the API provide customers with the ability to query questions made through the add-on using filters, for example, querying the last ten questions made by a specific user. The problem here is that the filter by username does not work.

h4. API Definition and Documentation
We can find a description of the API REST resources [here|https://docs.atlassian.com/confluence-questions/rest/index.html]. Deep diving on its resources, we can find the [Questions related options|https://docs.atlassian.com/confluence-questions/rest/resource_QuestionResource.html]. There's also a [WADL Document|https://docs.atlassian.com/confluence-questions/rest/application.wadl] that describes the API and its resources.

h4. Examples
As described in Atlassian Documentation, the API Call that could possibly bring ten questions made by a specific user would be the following:
{code}
http://CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL/rest/questions/1.0/question?username=admin&limit=10
{code}

However, after using this call in our browser, the return look like below:
{code}
[{"id":327718,"title":"I think I know who administrator is. Where should I spread the word?","url":"/display/AD/questions/327718/i-think-i-know-who-administrator-is.-where-should-i-spread-the-word","author":{"name":"alfabeta","fullName":"Alfa Delta","email":"alfa@beta.com","userKey":"8a8180845fff8c7601602d3901f50002"},"friendlyDateAsked":"Dec 06, 2017","dateAsked":1512587275222,"answersCount":0,"topics":

[{"id":655364,"idAsString":"655364","name":"adminlife","url":"/questions/topics/655364/adminlife","featured":false,"isWatching":false}],"votes":{"up":0,"down":0,"total":0,"upVoted":false,"downVoted":false},"space":{"spaceKey":"AD","spaceName":"Administrator"},"isTrashed":false},{"id":327714,"title":"Who's Administrator? What does he/she do for a living?","url":"/display/AD/questions/327714/whos-administrator-what-does-heshe-do-for-a-living","author":{"name":"admin","fullName":"admin","email":"admin@admin.com","userKey":"8a8180845fff8c76015fff8e457e0000"},"friendlyDateAsked":"Dec 06, 2017","dateAsked":1512587009181,"answersCount":0,"topics":
{code}

It returns questions made by different users, in this case, {{alfabeta}} and {{admin}}, even after I asked the API to return questions made by {{admin}} only.

h4. Suggested Root Cause
Questions are stored inside Confluence {{content}} table. We can quickly retrieve all questions existing in our application through the following query:
{code}
select * from content where pluginkey = 'com.atlassian.confluence.plugins.confluence-questions:question';
{code}
It is important to notice that the {{username}} column does not hold any sort of data but {{null}} entries. Also, it is important to notice that the {{username}} column is actually a Foreign Key that maps to the {{user_key}} column inside the {{user_mapping}} table and that the {{user_key}} column does not hold user names, but user ID's, which would read as below:
{code}
8a8180845fff8c7601602d3901f50002
{code}
This means that using the {{username}} as a filter in our REST call would never work, since there's no {{username}} in the table from where the plugin is retrieving data from.

h4. Workaround
There are two workarounds for this case. One of them is to query the database directly to retrieve the needed information:
{code}
select * from content where creator in (select user_key from user_mapping where username = 'admin')
and pluginkey = 'com.atlassian.confluence.plugins.confluence-questions:question';
{code}
Or, as there are no specific permissions to hide questions in the plugin, you can simply use an URL to retrieve the questions made by a specific user:
{code}
http://CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL/questions/users?username=admin
{code}
